1
00:02:12,937 --> 00:02:15,511
Is he conscious yet?
- No.

2
00:02:16,964 --> 00:02:18,857
Want to see him?

3
00:02:31,041 --> 00:02:32,661
Will he live?

4
00:02:33,657 --> 00:02:36,802
All I can say is that
he survived the operation.

5
00:02:40,848 --> 00:02:43,801
You shouldn't have bothered.
I'd have called for you.

6
00:02:45,057 --> 00:02:46,365
Is he dead?

7
00:02:46,530 --> 00:02:48,723
No, but he's still unconscious.

8
00:02:50,290 --> 00:02:52,378
It has been three days already...

9
00:02:52,378 --> 00:02:54,278
I wonder if it's worth the trouble
to intervene.

10
00:02:55,551 --> 00:02:57,638
If he could be moved...

11
00:02:58,375 --> 00:03:01,457
...we could start the experiment now.

12
00:03:02,057 --> 00:03:03,257
We'll think about it.

13
00:03:04,099 --> 00:03:06,227
Any dying person can be
maintained like that.

14
00:03:06,427 --> 00:03:08,149
Who knows?
- We do.

15
00:03:08,850 --> 00:03:10,424
The experience would kill him.

16
00:03:11,152 --> 00:03:12,821
We need a healthy man.

17
00:03:17,219 --> 00:03:18,728
There he is.

18
00:03:22,291 --> 00:03:24,217
Will you talk to him now?

19
00:03:25,148 --> 00:03:27,363
I'd rather wait.

20
00:03:28,423 --> 00:03:31,153
Has he seen anyone?
- He doesn't want to see anyone.

21
00:03:32,339 --> 00:03:35,516
Why don't you want to do the experiment
with one of your men?

22
00:03:36,537 --> 00:03:40,383
You do have volunteers, didn't you?
- Many, but they weren't suitable.

23
00:03:40,525 --> 00:03:42,291
But why him?

24
00:03:42,836 --> 00:03:45,455
He has nothing to lose.
That's what we're looking for.

25
00:03:45,468 --> 00:03:49,996
Why not pick a convict?
Offer him a pardon.

26
00:03:50,541 --> 00:03:52,179
That is not an option.

27
00:03:56,705 --> 00:04:00,301
Does he have any chance
of returning?

28
00:04:01,777 --> 00:04:02,966
It's impossible to predict.

29
00:04:03,966 --> 00:04:06,166
This is the first time it's
being done with a man.

30
00:04:08,037 --> 00:04:09,642
I'd like to meet him.

31
00:04:10,413 --> 00:04:13,334
I'll call him for you.
Wait a minute.

32
00:04:18,406 --> 00:04:20,492
You left your things
back in your room.

33
00:04:21,166 --> 00:04:23,254
Thanks. I won't need them.

34
00:04:38,373 --> 00:04:40,332
Claude Ridder?

35
00:04:41,832 --> 00:04:42,832
Yes, that's me.

36
00:04:43,018 --> 00:04:45,509
Do you have a moment,
or rather, a day?

37
00:04:48,347 --> 00:04:52,700
No, we're not the police.
I'm from Crespel Research Centre.

38
00:04:53,972 --> 00:04:55,910
Crespel? Never heard of it.

39
00:04:56,076 --> 00:04:58,077
Nobody has.

40
00:04:58,277 --> 00:05:02,077
 If you have no other plans for today,
I'd like to take you there.

41
00:05:02,946 --> 00:05:04,580
Is it far?

42
00:05:04,654 --> 00:05:06,681
Some 50 km.
We have a car.

43
00:05:07,929 --> 00:05:10,530
How's the weather?
Sunny.

44
00:05:11,428 --> 00:05:13,098
Then why not.

45
00:05:13,698 --> 00:05:14,898
- The taxi.
- I'll take care of it.

46
00:05:21,701 --> 00:05:24,815
Want to go by your house?
- No thanks.

47
00:05:30,819 --> 00:05:33,129
Am I the man you want?

48
00:05:33,529 --> 00:05:34,477
Without a doubt.

49
00:05:34,678 --> 00:05:37,278
This isn't a kidnapping.

50
00:05:37,848 --> 00:05:39,903
It wouldn't go well for you.
I have no family.

51
00:05:47,297 --> 00:05:50,283
What's Crespel like?

52
00:05:51,054 --> 00:05:54,071
It's a place that doesn't exist yet.

53
00:05:55,033 --> 00:05:58,018
Is it pretty?
Not particularly.

54
00:06:07,746 --> 00:06:09,288
Are you tired?

55
00:06:09,801 --> 00:06:11,567
I've been asked the same thing
every hour for three weeks.

56
00:06:12,208 --> 00:06:13,780
Have you recovered well?

57
00:06:14,167 --> 00:06:15,931
Why so much interest in me?

58
00:06:24,343 --> 00:06:26,129
Can you smoke?

59
00:06:26,429 --> 00:06:28,855
Yes, I'm better now.

60
00:06:29,456 --> 00:06:32,229
Apart from cancer, I have
nothing to worry about.

61
00:06:33,299 --> 00:06:35,546
Glad you were saved?

62
00:06:36,221 --> 00:06:37,890
I'm not sure I was saved.

63
00:06:56,220 --> 00:06:58,242
We're nearly there.

64
00:07:00,041 --> 00:07:02,674
You don't seem too worried.
- It's all the same to me.

65
00:07:02,858 --> 00:07:04,655
What else would you like
to happen to me?

66
00:07:05,498 --> 00:07:07,166
What if it's something extraordinary?

67
00:07:07,970 --> 00:07:09,995
Really, as in fairy tales?

68
00:07:56,373 --> 00:07:58,298
You were right.
It isn't very pretty.

69
00:07:58,909 --> 00:08:00,449
But not without interest.

70
00:08:00,833 --> 00:08:03,242
This is Crespel?
- Yes, here.

71
00:08:04,542 --> 00:08:05,942
I thought it was a town.

72
00:08:06,085 --> 00:08:09,477
There is one 5 km away,
but it's not Crespel.

73
00:08:10,657 --> 00:08:12,680
The boss will see you straight away.

74
00:08:50,111 --> 00:08:52,808
Surprised?
Frankly, yes.

75
00:08:53,610 --> 00:08:56,151
The Centre has existed for 15 years.

76
00:08:56,251 --> 00:08:59,251
Around here it's assumed
we study agriculture.

77
00:08:59,324 --> 00:09:02,399
But the subject of agriculture
is unknown to us.

78
00:09:02,599 --> 00:09:05,099
Our object of study is time.

79
00:09:06,130 --> 00:09:08,570
Have you figured it out?
- Partially.

80
00:09:08,891 --> 00:09:11,331
Where do I come in?

81
00:09:12,455 --> 00:09:18,036
I have a question for you, Mr. Ridder,
if you'd like to answer it.

82
00:09:18,236 --> 00:09:19,536
All right.

83
00:09:19,902 --> 00:09:22,792
I suppose you had a reason
to have attempted suicide...

84
00:09:23,692 --> 00:09:24,792
Yes...

85
00:09:24,968 --> 00:09:26,676
Have you changed your mind?

86
00:09:26,876 --> 00:09:28,476
It may be necessary to ask this
question again.

87
00:09:29,176 --> 00:09:31,676
- Who for?
- For you.

88
00:09:32,936 --> 00:09:36,081
No, it hasn't changed.

89
00:09:36,691 --> 00:09:38,521
You'd do it again?

90
00:09:41,186 --> 00:09:43,498
I am the perfect guinea pig, right?

91
00:09:44,332 --> 00:09:46,643
A volunteer who does not cling to life?

92
00:09:48,346 --> 00:09:51,554
If I accept, what chance
do I have of surviving?

93
00:09:53,578 --> 00:09:55,374
100% if you were a mouse.

94
00:09:57,589 --> 00:09:59,420
Let me show you something.

95
00:10:01,860 --> 00:10:03,337
The passage of time, no doubt.

96
00:10:03,937 --> 00:10:05,437
I need to think about it.

97
00:10:06,803 --> 00:10:09,821
I found interesting your idea
of a municipal agency...

98
00:10:10,366 --> 00:10:12,966
...to distribute time around
the city as it sees fit.

99
00:10:13,802 --> 00:10:16,081
It wouldn't work.
- Time would break down.

100
00:10:16,623 --> 00:10:19,126
I always thought we should
have a team of novelists...

101
00:10:19,933 --> 00:10:23,303
paid to put their wild ideas on paper.

102
00:10:27,389 --> 00:10:28,995
In this jar is mouse A;
in the other, mouse B.

103
00:10:30,086 --> 00:10:33,007
Look at them.
Do you see any difference?

104
00:10:33,874 --> 00:10:35,640
I don't know. Is one a female
and the other male?

105
00:10:36,314 --> 00:10:38,753
No, both are males.
But mouse B is a pioneer.

106
00:10:39,523 --> 00:10:41,385
A has never left his jar.

107
00:10:42,059 --> 00:10:45,046
B travelled in time and went back to
live for one minute in his past.

108
00:10:45,719 --> 00:10:47,453
A hero. When did this happen?

109
00:10:48,288 --> 00:10:50,181
Yesterday. With no ill effects.

110
00:10:50,631 --> 00:10:54,001
How do you be sure
that he travelled in time?

111
00:10:55,607 --> 00:10:57,436
That's the problem.

112
00:10:57,758 --> 00:11:00,455
We're confident it happened,
but he can't tell us.

113
00:11:00,961 --> 00:11:02,643
The technicians thought of everything.

114
00:11:02,743 --> 00:11:07,143
They should have taught him to speak
before doing the experiment.

115
00:11:08,127 --> 00:11:10,598
You'll go back exactly one year
into your past.

116
00:11:11,914 --> 00:11:15,511
And the experience won't last any more
than one minute.

117
00:11:17,050 --> 00:11:19,041
What if it kills me?

118
00:11:19,845 --> 00:11:24,789
With the treatment we've devised,
that won't happen.

119
00:11:26,873 --> 00:11:28,672
Where were you
this time last year?

120
00:11:32,653 --> 00:11:34,385
On holiday.

121
00:11:36,569 --> 00:11:41,416
I had 3 months off last year.
I was in France, on the Riviera.

122
00:11:42,090 --> 00:11:43,728
Are you sure?

123
00:11:44,070 --> 00:11:46,439
My memories are organised
around my holidays.

124
00:11:47,043 --> 00:11:49,423
You'll be in a  sort of sphere.

125
00:11:50,098 --> 00:11:53,628
When you return you must wait
four minutes to recover.

126
00:11:54,303 --> 00:11:55,939
Four minutes? Why?

127
00:11:56,339 --> 00:11:58,039
I'll explain.

128
00:11:59,279 --> 00:12:02,429
In a way,
we could compare it...

129
00:12:02,563 --> 00:12:07,332
...to the decompression chamber
that divers use.

130
00:12:09,615 --> 00:12:12,536
Are you interested?
- Not much.

131
00:12:14,045 --> 00:12:18,057
Why the past instead of the future?
Wouldn't it be more interesting?

132
00:12:18,533 --> 00:12:20,435
I agree with you.

133
00:12:20,635 --> 00:12:24,600
The result may not seem
very spectacular

134
00:12:24,900 --> 00:12:28,000
But  for the moment
we can't go further.

135
00:12:29,422 --> 00:12:31,572
So we've started with
only small steps.

136
00:12:31,772 --> 00:12:33,572
An experience that
barely seems interesting.

137
00:12:35,553 --> 00:12:38,121
No heart problems?
Nothing, not even a small ulcer?

138
00:12:38,507 --> 00:12:40,593
You're quite healthy.

139
00:12:41,333 --> 00:12:43,997
You see, suicide is
good for your health.

140
00:12:44,735 --> 00:12:47,656
You'll have to stay here
for a few days.

141
00:12:48,265 --> 00:12:49,935
On some kind of diet?

142
00:12:50,610 --> 00:12:54,493
Sort of.
Only for four days.

143
00:12:56,581 --> 00:13:00,690
Will I have to sign a release
before the experiment?

144
00:13:01,782 --> 00:13:03,546
I suppose so.

145
00:13:05,281 --> 00:13:08,233
If something goes wrong,
you could say I died in hospital.

146
00:13:09,003 --> 00:13:10,545
Absolutely.

147
00:13:10,618 --> 00:13:11,992
Good thinking.

148
00:13:13,594 --> 00:13:15,920
Was it your first suicide?
- Yes.

149
00:13:17,993 --> 00:13:19,437
With a gun?
- Yes.

150
00:13:22,199 --> 00:13:24,316
I can't imagine you with a gun.
- Neither can I.

151
00:13:25,055 --> 00:13:27,014
That's why I failed.

152
00:13:29,324 --> 00:13:31,507
Are you afraid?
- No.

153
00:13:32,214 --> 00:13:35,938
I've been afraid all my life...

154
00:13:36,484 --> 00:13:38,281
But not anymore.

155
00:13:38,520 --> 00:13:40,732
Do you sleep well?
- Very well.

156
00:13:40,832 --> 00:13:43,232
No headaches?
- No.

157
00:13:44,229 --> 00:13:47,492
We'll see tomorrow.
I have to observe the effects of T. 5.

158
00:13:47,729 --> 00:13:49,770
Doesn't seem to hurt you.

159
00:13:50,777 --> 00:13:53,013
Now we just have to wait.
- Three more days.

160
00:13:53,583 --> 00:13:55,809
What will happen to me
if I stay for years?

161
00:13:56,376 --> 00:14:00,329
It will only last 60 seconds.
We know because of the mice.

162
00:14:51,089 --> 00:14:53,989
Can I go in?
I won't wake up among pirates?

163
00:14:59,189 --> 00:15:02,238
You'll lie down.
We'll close the door.

164
00:15:03,362 --> 00:15:08,178
You'll go back one year,
then come back here a minute later.

165
00:15:10,111 --> 00:15:11,909
Disappointed?

166
00:15:12,453 --> 00:15:13,873
A bit.

167
00:15:16,173 --> 00:15:19,773
I expected a kind of... laboratory.

168
00:15:20,673 --> 00:15:22,773
Something electric.

169
00:15:24,878 --> 00:15:27,671
What if, for example... it fails?

170
00:15:28,345 --> 00:15:29,719
Impossible.

171
00:15:30,219 --> 00:15:34,219
You'll go back to September 5, 1966
at precisely 4 p.m.

172
00:15:34,893 --> 00:15:37,333
Why 4 p.m.?

173
00:15:38,328 --> 00:15:41,796
It's the time we chose.
We always sent the mice at that time...

174
00:15:42,033 --> 00:15:44,139
And they always came back.
- It became a habit.

175
00:15:44,846 --> 00:15:46,771
I never thought that scientists
would be superstitious!

176
00:15:47,510 --> 00:15:50,527
Why was I chosen, I wonder?

177
00:15:51,201 --> 00:15:53,064
Let's say our computer chose you.

178
00:15:53,270 --> 00:15:55,359
Out of millions, of course.
- Sure.

179
00:15:55,559 --> 00:15:57,459
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

180
00:15:58,168 --> 00:15:59,548
There's nothing to worry about.

181
00:16:00,121 --> 00:16:04,182
As we increase the dose
of T.5., you'll sleep more and more.

182
00:16:05,038 --> 00:16:07,091
I talk in my sleep.

183
00:16:07,638 --> 00:16:10,815
That is also an effect of T.5.
And when you wake up?

184
00:16:11,523 --> 00:16:13,192
I feel all right.

185
00:16:14,264 --> 00:16:16,627
Tomorrow, one hour before
entering the sphere ...

186
00:16:16,732 --> 00:16:19,804
we will inject you with
a large dose of T.5.

187
00:16:21,120 --> 00:16:24,216
You'll be drugged but
perfectly lucid.

188
00:16:24,516 --> 00:16:25,920
Don't worry.

189
00:16:26,120 --> 00:16:27,720
The treatment has prepared you
for this stage.

190
00:16:28,921 --> 00:16:30,912
Will I be able to move?

191
00:16:31,586 --> 00:16:34,468
The experiment requires that the subject
be completely passive.

192
00:16:34,668 --> 00:16:36,468
But you will be able to remember.

193
00:16:36,594 --> 00:16:38,568
Asleep but awake.

194
00:19:32,168 --> 00:19:33,368
Is it good?

195
00:19:36,037 --> 00:19:37,823
Coming?
- Later

196
00:19:40,614 --> 00:19:44,434
Two sea snakes and
a few sharks.

197
00:19:44,969 --> 00:19:47,280
That's about all.

198
00:20:03,680 --> 00:20:05,580
- Is it good?
- Very good.

199
00:20:05,594 --> 00:20:06,954
Did you see many fish?

200
00:20:07,497 --> 00:20:10,933
Two sea snakes and
a few sharks.

201
00:20:11,702 --> 00:20:13,949
That's about all.

202
00:20:18,027 --> 00:20:20,723
I don't like that apparatus.

203
00:20:21,045 --> 00:20:23,324
You always say that.

204
00:20:35,523 --> 00:20:37,193
Was it good?
- Yes.

205
00:20:37,194 --> 00:20:38,862
Did you see many fish?

206
00:20:45,571 --> 00:20:46,752
Let's go out for dinner.

207
00:20:47,552 --> 00:20:48,752
If you want to.

208
00:20:50,419 --> 00:20:53,212
Coming?
Later.

209
00:21:14,462 --> 00:21:16,806
It couldn't end any other way.

210
00:21:30,384 --> 00:21:32,087
About 4 months.

211
00:21:32,825 --> 00:21:35,778
How long will dedicate
yourself to packing?

212
00:21:36,453 --> 00:21:38,410
As long as there are
things to send.

213
00:21:38,582 --> 00:21:41,270
It seems you've developed
a good reputation in packing..

214
00:21:41,470 --> 00:21:44,970
I believe we could use
that energy better in something else.

215
00:21:45,794 --> 00:21:49,646
You could manage a line,
hold a responsible position.

216
00:21:50,385 --> 00:21:52,182
I hate responsibility.

217
00:21:52,857 --> 00:21:55,306
I felt the same at your age.

218
00:21:55,506 --> 00:21:57,706
C'mon, let's have a coffee.

219
00:21:58,410 --> 00:22:00,722
Rich family?
- Pretty well off, yes.

220
00:22:01,299 --> 00:22:02,809
At your age I had debts.

221
00:22:10,309 --> 00:22:12,509
- Is it good?
- Very good.

222
00:22:13,523 --> 00:22:14,976
See many fish?

223
00:22:15,714 --> 00:22:18,571
Two sea snakes and
a few sharks.

224
00:22:36,419 --> 00:22:38,045
We've lost him.

225
00:22:43,567 --> 00:22:45,188
Every time, the same thing.

226
00:22:52,912 --> 00:22:56,057
What time did she come?
- At nine.

227
00:22:57,567 --> 00:23:00,295
If we want to send out those 5,000 circulars
by this afternoon, everyone will have to work.

228
00:23:00,936 --> 00:23:03,568
Imagine, she hasn't even
done 100 yet!

229
00:23:04,980 --> 00:23:07,357
In four hours?

230
00:23:08,192 --> 00:23:11,434
One envelope for each 2 minutes.
Quite a performance.

231
00:23:12,332 --> 00:23:15,383
It's a record.
Is she pretty?

232
00:23:15,883 --> 00:23:17,083
Who?

233
00:23:17,437 --> 00:23:19,235
The record-breaker.

234
00:23:20,326 --> 00:23:22,124
In a way.
- In a way?

235
00:23:22,862 --> 00:23:24,693
Send her in.

236
00:23:35,993 --> 00:23:37,493
Left.

237
00:23:37,853 --> 00:23:40,321
See, even your car is a problem.

238
00:23:41,138 --> 00:23:43,256
Shall we stop
for lunch in an hour?

239
00:23:43,962 --> 00:23:45,663
If you like.

240
00:23:47,717 --> 00:23:48,814
I don't know.

241
00:23:49,314 --> 00:23:52,214
Something about Catherine bothers me.

242
00:23:52,405 --> 00:23:55,493
Perhaps the fact that
you don't unsettle her?

243
00:23:55,693 --> 00:23:59,209
You're a quiet sort aren't you?
- When I have nothing to say, yes.

244
00:23:59,449 --> 00:24:01,790
What did you do when you met her?
- Nothing.

245
00:24:01,810 --> 00:24:04,539
And now?
- Not much.

246
00:24:05,082 --> 00:24:07,140
Not much.
Let's stop here to eat.

247
00:24:29,964 --> 00:24:32,725
The effect of the T. 5. is weak anyway.

248
00:24:33,239 --> 00:24:35,261
Seven minutes.
- He's come back 5 times already.

249
00:24:38,759 --> 00:24:41,104
The transition period
always scares me.

250
00:24:41,509 --> 00:24:43,861
Why not get him out before the
four minutes are up?

251
00:24:43,870 --> 00:24:46,628
Because he could stay
like that for weeks.

252
00:24:46,881 --> 00:24:49,611
We'll wait.
- If we wait he'll starve.

253
00:24:50,285 --> 00:24:53,206
It's odd to see it all
from a heated train.

254
00:24:53,881 --> 00:24:55,999
Was it cold?
Very cold.

255
00:24:56,930 --> 00:24:59,762
In a few minutes we'll pass
a town I liberated.

256
00:24:59,962 --> 00:25:02,062
Were you alone?
- Almost.

257
00:25:02,185 --> 00:25:04,400
We were about 50...

258
00:25:04,666 --> 00:25:06,528
...against many Germans.

259
00:25:07,234 --> 00:25:09,578
Guns don't suit you.

260
00:25:10,253 --> 00:25:11,986
I never got used to them.

261
00:25:21,970 --> 00:25:25,983
There might be a street
with your name on it.

262
00:25:26,592 --> 00:25:28,936
It wasn't so amusing back then.

263
00:25:29,723 --> 00:25:32,697
Why didn't you come on Wednesday?
- I forgot.

264
00:25:33,558 --> 00:25:36,608
Come tonight,
both of you.

265
00:25:36,878 --> 00:25:38,484
Which two?
- You and Catherine.

266
00:25:39,755 --> 00:25:41,361
It'll be difficult.
We've separated.

267
00:25:41,561 --> 00:25:44,861
How long were you together for?
- Seven years.

268
00:25:44,907 --> 00:25:46,828
Come alone if you like, then.

269
00:25:48,294 --> 00:25:50,701
Aren't you afraid of having
that dirty wall behind you?

270
00:25:51,503 --> 00:25:53,848
The papers on the table
scare me more.

271
00:25:59,143 --> 00:26:04,312
We should redecorate your office.
Paintings and tapestries.

272
00:26:05,314 --> 00:26:08,364
In your office, for example,
a big picture...

273
00:26:09,208 --> 00:26:13,763
...of an unpaid bill
dated February 17, 1951.

274
00:26:14,746 --> 00:26:17,475
The bookkeeper removed a
heap of commas.

275
00:26:17,747 --> 00:26:20,170
He is struggling against effectiveness.

276
00:26:26,914 --> 00:26:28,325
An eraser...

277
00:26:28,999 --> 00:26:30,540
...and no pencil?

278
00:26:30,737 --> 00:26:32,216
I hate pencils.

279
00:26:32,316 --> 00:26:33,516
And the rubbers?
- No.

280
00:26:33,616 --> 00:26:35,216
Because they are useless
without a pencil.

281
00:26:35,216 --> 00:26:37,216
Hello
- Hello

282
00:26:37,677 --> 00:26:41,336
Compliments of the author...
Compliments of the author...

283
00:26:42,075 --> 00:26:44,258
You don't have much imagination.

284
00:26:44,836 --> 00:26:46,820
I don't know her.
I don't know what to say.

285
00:27:11,050 --> 00:27:15,288
A swimmer got drowned.

286
00:27:15,962 --> 00:27:17,342
Is he dead?
- For a good while.

287
00:27:19,428 --> 00:27:20,937
He was a good swimmer.

288
00:27:21,915 --> 00:27:25,382
He must have swum for hours
before he drowned.

289
00:27:26,182 --> 00:27:29,882
For hours, you realize?
- Claude.

290
00:27:30,791 --> 00:27:32,365
Be quiet.

291
00:27:32,706 --> 00:27:34,278
You do not need me.

292
00:27:34,313 --> 00:27:36,050
You only need what is right here.

293
00:27:36,250 --> 00:27:38,150
You could have me embalmed
and put in a corner.

294
00:27:38,221 --> 00:27:41,186
But I'm alive, I move,
come, go, see people.

295
00:27:41,192 --> 00:27:43,375
If I didn't,
I'd kill myself.

296
00:27:43,450 --> 00:27:46,497
The more I give you,
the worse you get.

297
00:27:59,323 --> 00:28:01,723
I don't think I understand you anymore.

298
00:28:02,423 --> 00:28:03,723
I'm leaving.

299
00:28:10,052 --> 00:28:11,650
Tomorrow, I am leaving.

300
00:28:28,419 --> 00:28:29,863
It's 3 p.m.

301
00:28:32,652 --> 00:28:34,514
However, there are still
3 hours to go.

302
00:28:36,537 --> 00:28:38,817
3 minutes ago it was 3 p. m.

303
00:28:40,998 --> 00:28:43,567
In 3 weeks it will be 3 p. m.

304
00:28:45,365 --> 00:28:46,841
In a century too.

305
00:28:47,933 --> 00:28:50,333
Time passes for everybody
but for me...

306
00:28:50,537 --> 00:28:52,831
...stuck in this room...

307
00:28:53,131 --> 00:28:54,831
...It doesn't pass.

308
00:28:57,146 --> 00:28:58,977
Search for your time.

309
00:29:00,324 --> 00:29:02,283
It's 3 p. m. forever.

310
00:29:04,483 --> 00:29:05,683
Hello?

311
00:29:13,014 --> 00:29:14,462
Hello...

312
00:29:15,994 --> 00:29:18,370
On the third beep it will be exactly...

313
00:29:18,470 --> 00:29:22,170
Exactly three o'clock,
zero minutes, zero seconds.

314
00:29:22,251 --> 00:29:24,400
Pardon? All right...

315
00:29:25,139 --> 00:29:27,226
...tomorrow at the same time,
as we agreed.

316
00:29:28,445 --> 00:29:30,179
Love to the family.

317
00:29:36,383 --> 00:29:38,406
For 100 million years...

318
00:29:38,445 --> 00:29:40,600
...the Earth belonged to
algae and molluscs...

319
00:29:40,934 --> 00:29:43,109
...and then reptiles ruled the earth...

320
00:29:43,440 --> 00:29:46,756
...until this company I'm
working for was created.

321
00:29:47,836 --> 00:29:52,624
I believe that I'm travelling from
birth to death at 100,000 kph

322
00:29:53,365 --> 00:29:57,853
The earth will spin for
millions of years more without me...

323
00:29:58,658 --> 00:30:03,071
And  as a result,
I'm here, using a pencil...

324
00:30:03,414 --> 00:30:07,629
...to express our sincere
regrets to a customer...

325
00:30:07,829 --> 00:30:10,229
...for the loss of his shipment sent
on the fourth...

326
00:30:13,036 --> 00:30:15,476
and to tell him that we'll do
all we can to...

327
00:30:15,576 --> 00:30:16,776
Ready?

328
00:30:17,976 --> 00:30:18,676
Yes.

329
00:30:21,159 --> 00:30:23,113
What?
What's a mouse doing here?

330
00:30:23,847 --> 00:30:26,102
Did you say something?
- No.

331
00:30:27,322 --> 00:30:29,770
I just saw a mouse.
- So?

332
00:30:30,178 --> 00:30:33,206
Have you ever seen
a mouse on a beach!

333
00:30:33,549 --> 00:30:35,122
Maybe it's on vacation.

334
00:30:39,522 --> 00:30:41,022
How was it?

335
00:30:43,211 --> 00:30:45,009
In a sense it was successful.

336
00:30:45,426 --> 00:30:47,546
He isn't dead.
On the other hand...

337
00:30:49,027 --> 00:30:50,304
A time race.

338
00:30:50,504 --> 00:30:53,004
Office time against outside time.

339
00:30:53,006 --> 00:30:55,991
Who's winning?
Don't know yet.

340
00:30:56,667 --> 00:31:00,044
She's pretty, yes,
looks like your kind.

341
00:31:00,315 --> 00:31:03,718
Beautiful, clean, modest...

342
00:31:03,792 --> 00:31:07,011
Things that I despise.
- You like me because you hate almost everything.

343
00:31:07,452 --> 00:31:10,245
I like things that are changeable.

344
00:31:10,855 --> 00:31:12,878
Am I changeable?

345
00:31:13,808 --> 00:31:14,652
Not really.

346
00:31:15,552 --> 00:31:16,752
Not absolutely.

347
00:31:18,495 --> 00:31:23,282
Rather, you are ... surprising.
A swamp.

348
00:31:23,392 --> 00:31:25,572
A dark night...

349
00:31:26,777 --> 00:31:30,181
One would rather wring your neck
than smile at you...

350
00:31:31,368 --> 00:31:33,689
...or slowly melt into you...

351
00:31:33,889 --> 00:31:35,089
..and sink.

352
00:31:36,600 --> 00:31:39,729
I can't imagine Monique
outside your window.

353
00:31:39,973 --> 00:31:42,323
You reek of low tide...

354
00:31:43,023 --> 00:31:45,323
drownings, octopus.

355
00:31:47,654 --> 00:31:50,886
Behind, this beach.
- This beach is me...

356
00:31:51,239 --> 00:31:53,198
I need you.

357
00:31:54,417 --> 00:31:57,661
I have needed you since
in the office they told me...

358
00:31:58,334 --> 00:32:01,417
...of a girl who hated envelopes.

359
00:32:02,379 --> 00:32:04,177
...and work.

360
00:32:06,456 --> 00:32:09,571
Let's make love.

361
00:32:11,528 --> 00:32:13,166
Here, on the sand?

362
00:32:17,659 --> 00:32:20,839
I'd run away to a land
without nights...

363
00:32:24,073 --> 00:32:26,784
You know what?
Your wife has a nice behind.

364
00:32:27,675 --> 00:32:30,855
I'll tell you what you see
right now.

365
00:32:31,688 --> 00:32:34,128
You're by a window, no?
Let me see...

366
00:32:34,834 --> 00:32:37,692
Everything is blue...

367
00:32:38,463 --> 00:32:41,319
...the sea, the sand,
the town...

368
00:32:41,961 --> 00:32:43,953
Even the people are blue...

369
00:32:44,262 --> 00:32:46,721
And the many beautiful girls
that caught your attention...

370
00:32:47,194 --> 00:32:49,441
I miss you Claude...

371
00:32:50,564 --> 00:32:54,161
It both bothers me,
knowing that I miss you.

372
00:32:54,762 --> 00:32:56,125
It's the first time...

373
00:32:57,449 --> 00:32:59,093
I was always unaffected.

374
00:32:59,293 --> 00:33:02,393
I was always indifferent to the
presence or absence of things

375
00:33:03,790 --> 00:33:06,102
Perhaps there's a white sail
in the distance.

376
00:33:06,177 --> 00:33:09,256
I also see some seagulls
spiralling down to the beach.

377
00:33:09,602 --> 00:33:11,688
Are there any on the Costa Azul?

378
00:33:12,234 --> 00:33:14,674
They bring rain...

379
00:33:14,994 --> 00:33:16,632
It never rains there.

380
00:33:19,257 --> 00:33:22,606
We're wasting time, Ridder.
We'll never finish the circulars tonight.

381
00:33:23,181 --> 00:33:24,913
And you keep turning that crank.

382
00:33:28,690 --> 00:33:31,056
It's always beautiful.
- It's beautiful.

383
00:33:35,251 --> 00:33:37,563
Here nature doesn't have
that ugly green of the countryside.

384
00:33:39,938 --> 00:33:41,928
Coming?
Later.

385
00:33:47,063 --> 00:33:50,250
And if I'd been married?
- I do not know what would have done.

386
00:33:50,550 --> 00:33:52,250
I wouldn't have cared, surely.

387
00:33:53,446 --> 00:33:56,848
When I met you,
I felt nothing special.

388
00:33:57,755 --> 00:33:59,905
It was a matter of... your being different.

389
00:34:02,087 --> 00:34:06,839
You were really out of your
element at the office.

390
00:34:07,996 --> 00:34:10,017
I knew the rest
didn't matter.

391
00:34:10,339 --> 00:34:13,371
You could have been indifferent.
- No, not at all.

392
00:34:16,181 --> 00:34:21,165
I was so scared that night,
when we left the restaurant.

393
00:34:22,376 --> 00:34:25,620
Did you quit your job for no other
reason than to impress me?

394
00:34:26,229 --> 00:34:28,123
Yes. Were you impressed?

395
00:34:28,670 --> 00:34:31,237
Were you making
good money?

396
00:34:31,558 --> 00:34:33,998
A living.

397
00:34:43,146 --> 00:34:45,105
Have I told you that
your eyes are beautiful?

398
00:34:49,086 --> 00:34:51,269
And I want you.
- Me too.

399
00:34:52,469 --> 00:34:54,469
See? We are not pioneers.

400
00:34:55,730 --> 00:34:57,497
Shall we answer?

401
00:34:59,487 --> 00:35:00,803
No.

402
00:35:11,515 --> 00:35:15,014
Catherine, I love you.

403
00:35:18,170 --> 00:35:19,935
Do you hear me?

404
00:35:21,819 --> 00:35:23,487
I love you.

405
00:35:26,156 --> 00:35:28,050
It was the only reason.

406
00:35:30,755 --> 00:35:34,576
Long before you died.

407
00:35:37,112 --> 00:35:38,748
And now I'm dead.

408
00:35:46,260 --> 00:35:48,186
I'm cold.

409
00:35:49,933 --> 00:35:52,084
I hear my own words.

410
00:35:54,509 --> 00:35:56,179
It's the drug...

411
00:36:00,801 --> 00:36:03,049
What are my chances
of surviving?

412
00:36:04,402 --> 00:36:08,314
Ah, yes, 100% if I were a mouse.

413
00:36:10,978 --> 00:36:13,386
I am a mouse then,
if I'm alive.

414
00:36:15,602 --> 00:36:19,004
They'll come now.

415
00:36:19,357 --> 00:36:21,251
There's still four
minutes to wait.

416
00:36:26,163 --> 00:36:29,598
And the mouse?
Where's the mouse?

417
00:36:33,985 --> 00:36:35,943
You're delirious!

418
00:36:36,360 --> 00:36:38,383
Unfortunately not.

419
00:36:42,884 --> 00:36:45,688
Claude, please stop.
You're scaring me.

420
00:36:45,831 --> 00:36:47,595
I don't mean to.

421
00:36:47,852 --> 00:36:50,437
I killed Catherine
two months ago in Glasgow.

422
00:36:52,429 --> 00:36:55,630
I went with her without telling anyone,
and I came back alone.

423
00:36:56,730 --> 00:36:57,730
I don't believe you.

424
00:36:57,804 --> 00:36:59,763
You're both right and wrong.

425
00:37:00,276 --> 00:37:01,785
What do you mean?

426
00:37:01,863 --> 00:37:04,185
You're right.
I'm not capable of killing.

427
00:37:05,360 --> 00:37:07,418
But you're wrong,
because I did.

428
00:37:07,596 --> 00:37:09,200
Impossible.

429
00:37:09,907 --> 00:37:12,304
I thought so too.

430
00:37:13,323 --> 00:37:15,081
What can we do?

431
00:37:15,281 --> 00:37:20,081
We won't get out of here
until they do away with trams.

432
00:37:20,155 --> 00:37:23,589
Buses are just as bad.

433
00:37:24,617 --> 00:37:28,950
Cars will be useless soon.

434
00:37:30,039 --> 00:37:32,340
I'll give you some advice, sir.

435
00:37:32,510 --> 00:37:35,977
I'd recommend that you hop out
and take the tram...

436
00:37:36,813 --> 00:37:38,609
...otherwise, you'll miss your train.

437
00:37:39,049 --> 00:37:40,897
Have you got time, sir?

438
00:37:41,566 --> 00:37:45,258
We'll have to cook
the cat's eyes.

439
00:37:48,437 --> 00:37:50,973
What?
- We have a cat, don't we.

440
00:37:53,606 --> 00:37:56,173
Are psychoses red?
- No. The future is red.

441
00:37:56,783 --> 00:37:58,164
And psychoses?

442
00:37:58,838 --> 00:38:00,411
I get them mixed up.

443
00:38:19,063 --> 00:38:20,732
Are you awake too?

444
00:38:21,774 --> 00:38:23,529
Go to the office for me.

445
00:38:29,402 --> 00:38:31,744
I need you.
- I'm hard to live with.

446
00:38:32,836 --> 00:38:34,506
I don't want
to live with you.

447
00:38:35,596 --> 00:38:37,299
I want to be with you.

448
00:38:39,159 --> 00:38:40,958
I want you to
stay with me tonight.

449
00:38:43,557 --> 00:38:45,548
Don't leave me.

450
00:38:48,212 --> 00:38:50,075
I'm afraid...
- Afraid?

451
00:38:50,116 --> 00:38:51,849
Yes, I'm afraid of
losing you.

452
00:38:51,949 --> 00:38:53,149
Of finding myself
alone tomorrow.

453
00:38:55,371 --> 00:38:57,170
Of being without you tonight.

454
00:38:59,319 --> 00:39:01,072
If you like, we could
spend the night in ...

455
00:39:29,848 --> 00:39:33,284
Last time he stayed in the sphere
for one minute 29.

456
00:39:34,184 --> 00:39:36,584
He arrived at 4 minutes 23.

457
00:39:37,939 --> 00:39:41,148
Now he's been gone for
3 minutes and 4 seconds...

458
00:39:53,269 --> 00:39:56,194
He's trapped in that minute,
reliving it endlessly.

459
00:39:56,205 --> 00:39:58,195
That's what gives us the best
chance of bringing him back.

460
00:39:58,806 --> 00:40:00,602
I couldn't stay there.

461
00:40:01,213 --> 00:40:03,395
Stay here if you like.
- No, I'm going home.

462
00:40:05,225 --> 00:40:06,670
Aren't you sleepy?

463
00:40:07,216 --> 00:40:08,886
She'd be sad
if you didn't come.

464
00:40:09,174 --> 00:40:13,154
Sad? She's always sad...

465
00:40:13,797 --> 00:40:16,847
...when I'm there...when I'm not...
...when she's asleep... when she's awake...

466
00:40:17,488 --> 00:40:20,378
Sometimes I think she's
sadness personified.

467
00:40:21,179 --> 00:40:23,587
You should be used to it,
after five years.

468
00:40:24,167 --> 00:40:27,954
I think of leaving her.

469
00:40:29,976 --> 00:40:32,064
I can't help her.
Nobody can help her.

470
00:40:32,834 --> 00:40:34,439
She needs you.

471
00:40:35,048 --> 00:40:36,687
That doesn't help.

472
00:40:38,804 --> 00:40:39,928
Could you leave her?

473
00:40:40,409 --> 00:40:42,047
Probably not.

474
00:40:43,010 --> 00:40:46,187
Sometimes I can't stand it.
I feel oxidized...

475
00:40:48,563 --> 00:40:50,444
Once I left...
- But you returned.

476
00:40:50,526 --> 00:40:51,835
Yes, after 2 days.

477
00:40:51,936 --> 00:40:55,244
She greeted me as if I'd been to the cinema
and asked if I had eaten well.

478
00:40:57,521 --> 00:40:59,317
Claude Ridder,
you've had it.

479
00:41:06,444 --> 00:41:09,418
At the time, she wanted
to have a house by the sea...

480
00:41:10,121 --> 00:41:11,950
...but was never sadder
than when we went to the Riviera.

481
00:41:12,550 --> 00:41:14,150
Perhaps she doesn't
like the sun.

482
00:41:14,358 --> 00:41:18,178
She loves the sun, but she can't
help thinking that one day it won't exist.

483
00:41:19,173 --> 00:41:22,159
You can't live with her
or without her.

484
00:41:22,833 --> 00:41:27,778
And so God created the Earth, looked at it
and said: "I'm just waiting for it to turn".

485
00:41:31,917 --> 00:41:33,555
You go to sleep.

486
00:41:34,134 --> 00:41:35,803
I'm not sleepy.

487
00:41:55,995 --> 00:41:58,371
You're not good at that.

488
00:41:58,980 --> 00:42:00,747
Not especially. I don't write anything.

489
00:42:01,934 --> 00:42:04,342
This job doesn't suit you.

490
00:42:05,111 --> 00:42:07,711
No job does.
Offices make me sick.

491
00:42:08,011 --> 00:42:10,111
They make you sick?
- Yes.

492
00:42:13,426 --> 00:42:15,995
Do you know what you've earned this morning?
- No.

493
00:42:16,284 --> 00:42:19,879
Exactly 14 francs.
Enough for a pack of cigarettes

494
00:42:20,384 --> 00:42:24,028
Not much, especially because
I won't be back after lunch.

495
00:42:25,445 --> 00:42:28,367
Did you expect to make money
in just one morning?

496
00:42:28,868 --> 00:42:30,760
For how long?

497
00:42:31,532 --> 00:42:34,018
I don't know.
A day... till tomorrow.

498
00:42:34,918 --> 00:42:36,118
Okay.

499
00:42:38,433 --> 00:42:40,552
Here's what we'll do...

500
00:42:43,870 --> 00:42:47,047
I'll give you the 14 francs I owe you...

501
00:42:50,643 --> 00:42:53,339
And you ask me to lunch
with that small fortune.

502
00:42:58,443 --> 00:43:00,659
Why?
- Because it doesn't interest me.

503
00:43:01,269 --> 00:43:02,939
You never buy anything.

504
00:43:03,516 --> 00:43:07,914
I do. Bread, milk, matches,
vegetables, tomatoes, mustard...

505
00:43:08,203 --> 00:43:10,450
Nothing for you.
- I don't need anything.

506
00:43:11,895 --> 00:43:14,592
You could buy a sweater...
- I've already got 2.

507
00:43:14,792 --> 00:43:16,092
That's not much, is it?

508
00:43:17,201 --> 00:43:20,410
No visits?
- No.

509
00:43:20,625 --> 00:43:22,393
I don't want to see anyone.

510
00:43:24,510 --> 00:43:26,661
How about we
stay out all night...

511
00:43:27,176 --> 00:43:29,454
We go to bed
very late.

512
00:43:30,225 --> 00:43:31,701
That's different.

513
00:43:33,371 --> 00:43:36,325
Hello. How are you today?

514
